column1: Will the closing price of Chevron stock be higher on 5 August 2020 than it was on 7 July 2020?
column6: ['Business']
It closed at $86.49
The trend is your friend....usually. And the trend is UP.

Trends over the past few months suggest the stock is fluctuating between low 80s and high 80s to low 90s. As it is currently trending upwards at 86.59, it has not yet reached the peak where is normally inverts and begins creeping downwards.
After a wild few days, it all comes down to the very last day with the stock at $86.49 at close today. $86.36 in after hours trading. A straight 50/50 shot.

July 9 mid day = 83.52 down 3% on the day. WTI=39.96 slightly off. Petroleum exploration, drilling, production and refining appear to be all under pressure. Well run companies as well as marginal ones feeling the pressure. Covid continues to stymie the best laid plans for returning to normal. Thus demand is off and supply is abundant.
An even shot (with a slightly bearish bias).

Predicting what will happen over the next four weeks is nearly impossible. Maybe a hedge fund manager will bet heavily one way or the other. But for someone like me, with very limited knowledge of the oil business, it's close to a coin flip. I would note that CVX has been in a trading range of about $85-95 for over two months. It's near the low of that range right now. So I'll start with a bet of 53%, on the assumption that it will stay inside its trading range. If it breaks out to the downside I'll flip hard towards NO.
Based on stock history. it may continue swinging slightly.

I think it is more of a beta-question here (30-d beta is around 1.5 towards S&P500), which suggest the stock is very sensitive to respective changes in the index. Chevron fell by more than 50 per cent in spring 2020 due to the blood bath on the oil market (their business model is long crude oil price by nature and long travel due to downstream products). As stocks in general are currently "ambitiously priced" to say the least considering political markets ahead of US presidential elections and economic reality, the S&P500 is likely to fall over the next month. High beta means Chevron is likely to exaggerate the drop and will fall even more. I guess the stock is going to see 65USD before it can turn better. Stabilizing crude oil markets and more demand for gas is likely to compensate for some of the recent troubles, and Chevron announced it is going to pay a dividend anyway (cashflows are likely still positive). But things are never going to be the same, easy cakewalk for Big Oil again, since the political will for a substitution of fossile fuels by sustainable energy production and a de-carbonization of the economies and most societies seems real this time.
Coin flip.
